1) Feature Engineering¶

As stated in the problem description that the category of CityTier are ordered in the following sequence:
Tier 1 > Tier 2 > Tier 3

However, the sequence of numerical representation is currently in this order: 1 < 2 < 3. We shall convert the numerical representation to its corresponding Tier level and then apply OrdinalEncoder to set its order accordingly.

In [7]:
# verifying the unique values of CityTier column
data['CityTier'].unique()
Out[7]:
array([3, 1, 2])
In [8]:
# mapping respective values of CityTier with its corresponding Tier level

df_CityTier = data[['CityTier']]
df_CityTier['DuplicatedCityTier'] = df_CityTier['CityTier'].copy()
df_CityTier['DuplicatedCityTier'].replace({
    1: 'Tier 1', 
    2: 'Tier 2', 
    3: 'Tier 3',

# While doing univariate analysis of numerical variables we want to study their central tendency and dispersion.
# Let us write a function that will help us create boxplot and histogram for any input numerical variable.
# This function takes the numerical column as the input and returns the boxplots and histograms for the variable.
# Let us see if this help us write faster and cleaner code.
def histogram_boxplot(feature, figsize=(15,10), bins = None):
    """ Boxplot and histogram combined
    feature: 1-d feature array
    figsize: size of fig (default (9,8))
    bins: number of bins (default None / auto)
    """
    sns.set(font_scale=2) # setting the font scale of the seaborn
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(nrows = 2, # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
                                           sharex = True, # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
                                           gridspec_kw = {"height_ratios": (.25, .75)}, 
                                           figsize = figsize 
                                           ) # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color='violet') # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(x=feature, kde=F, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins,palette="winter") if bins else sns.histplot(x=feature, kde=False, ax=ax_hist2) # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.mean(feature), color='green', linestyle='--') # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(np.median(feature), color='black', linestyle='-') # Add median to the histogram

# Function to create barplots that indicate percentage for each category.

def perc_on_bar(feature):
    '''
    plot
    feature: categorical feature
    the function won't work if a column is passed in hue parameter
    '''
    total = len(feature) # length of the column
    ax = sns.countplot(feature,palette='winter')
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total) # percentage of each class of the category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.15 # width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()           # hieght of the plot
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size = 12) # annotate the percantage 
    plt.show() # show the plot

## Function to plot stacked bar chart
def stacked_plot(x):
    sns.set(palette="nipy_spectral")
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(x, data["ProdTaken"], margins=True)
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 110)
    tab = pd.crosstab(x, data["ProdTaken"], normalize="index")
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(10, 5))
    plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.00, 1))
    plt.show()

(3421, 21) (1467, 21)

Model evaluation criterion¶

Model can make wrong predictions as:¶

  1. Predicting a customer would purchase the newly introduced travel package when he/she won't purchase it.
  2. Predicting a customer won't purchase the newly introduced travel package when he/she would actually purchase it.

Which case is more important?¶

  • If the model predicts a customer won't purchase the travel package but actually would purchase it so then the company lose the revenue that was supposed to be earned from that customer. In other words, false nagative is more impactful.

Which metric to optimize?¶

  • We would want wants Recall to be maximized, greater the recall lesser the chances of false negatives.

Let's define function to provide metric scores on train and test set and a function to show confusion matrix so that we do not have use the same code repetitively while evaluating models.

In [88]:
##  Function to calculate different metric scores of the model - Accuracy, Recall and Precision
def get_metrics_score(model,flag=True):
    '''
    model : classifier to predict values of X

    '''
    # defining an empty list to store train and test results
    score_list=[] 
    
    pred_train = model.predict(X_train)
    pred_test = model.predict(X_test)
    
    train_acc = model.score(X_train,y_train)
    test_acc = model.score(X_test,y_test)
    
    train_recall = metrics.recall_score(y_train,pred_train)
    test_recall = metrics.recall_score(y_test,pred_test)
    
    train_precision = metrics.precision_score(y_train,pred_train)
    test_precision = metrics.precision_score(y_test,pred_test)
    
    
    score_list.extend((train_acc,test_acc,train_recall,test_recall,train_precision,test_precision))
        
    # If the flag is set to True then only the following print statements will be dispayed. The default value is set to True.
    if flag == True: 
        print("Accuracy on training set : ",model.score(X_train,y_train))
        print("Accuracy on test set : ",model.score(X_test,y_test))
        print("Recall on training set : ",metrics.recall_score(y_train,pred_train))
        print("Recall on test set : ",metrics.recall_score(y_test,pred_test))
        print("Precision on training set : ",metrics.precision_score(y_train,pred_train))
        print("Precision on test set : ",metrics.precision_score(y_test,pred_test))
    
    return score_list # returning the list with train and test scores
In [89]:
## Function to create confusion matrix
def make_confusion_matrix(model,y_actual,labels=[1, 0]):
    '''
    model : classifier to predict values of X
    y_actual : ground truth  
    
    '''
    y_predict = model.predict(X_test)
    cm=metrics.confusion_matrix( y_actual, y_predict, labels=[0, 1])
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ["Actual - No","Actual - Yes"]],
                  columns = [i for i in ['Predicted - No','Predicted - Yes']])
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in
                cm.flatten()]
    group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in
                         cm.flatten()/np.sum(cm)]
    labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}" for v1, v2 in
              zip(group_counts,group_percentages)]
    labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)
    plt.figure(figsize = (10,7))
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=labels,fmt='')
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

7) Actionable Insights & Recommendations¶

  • On the basis of our analysis, we can say that a customer who will likely purchase the newly introduced travel package has the following features in comparison to one who wouln't purchase:
    • has a passport
    • current marital status is single
    • is being pitched the targeted product
    • designation of Senior Manager
    • from Tier-3 city
    • higher number of follow-ups
  • A Wellness Tourism Package, aiming at promoting a healthy lifestyle and increasing one's sense of well-being, is likely to cost more than a basic package. Hence, it might not be very afforable to an Executive. While customers who are a Senior Manager are the next group of customers with highest closure rate, we should target Senior Manager for pitching this product.
  • Also from our analysis, Senior Manager are from the middle-age group (33 to 49 years old), who are more likely to value healthy lifestyle than the young energetic Executives (25 to 35 years old). This is because they have worked longer years than the young.
  • Besides, the company should target Senior Manager from Tier-3 city, for higher success rate.
  • One strategy the company should implement is to qualify a customer by checking whether they have a passport, currently being single, a Senior Manager, and from Tier-3 city, in order to increase number of follow-ups. This would maximise the chance of deal closure for the newly introduced Wellness Tourism Package and in the meantime reducing marketing cost by avoiding salespersons to contact customers who are less likely to purchase the package.
